---
// §11 — FAQ. Question-led, answer-first prose. Native <details> (keyboard-accessible,
// no JS). No FAQPage schema (rich results retired 2026).
const qs = [
  { q: 'Do I have to write all the docs myself?', a: 'No. Point Atlas at a source — a git repo or a Jira project — and it reads the source, drafts cited markdown pages, scores them against the source’s real surface (a coverage %, with the gaps named at file:line), and publishes them as ordinary tela pages. Two source types today; more coming. You can still write and edit pages by hand alongside the generated ones.' },
  { q: 'What happens when my code changes?', a: 'Atlas probes each source for drift about every 15 minutes (a cheap no-clone check) and regenerates on a schedule you set — hourly, daily, weekly, monthly, or off — rebuilding only the sources that actually changed (a delta run over the changed files). Generated pages are the machine-maintained layer, so a re-run rewrites them. Atlas needs an LLM and an embedder — both on for the hosted instance; bring your own on self-host.' },
  { q: 'Does it work inside Claude and ChatGPT?', a: 'Yes. tela runs a remote MCP server with OAuth sign-in; add it as a connector in Claude or ChatGPT (it’s submitted to both directories) and your agent searches, reads, and writes your wiki — scoped to your account. Code agents like Claude Code or Cursor point at the same URL with a token.' },
  { q: 'How is search different from a normal wiki?', a: 'tela ranks results by meaning as well as by keyword, so a search returns the section that answers your question even when it doesn’t contain the exact words. Your team searches from the command palette; Claude and ChatGPT search the same way through the connector and get a link back to the source.' },
  { q: 'Can it answer questions, not just find pages?', a: 'Yes — that’s “ask your docs”. Ask in plain language and tela retrieves the relevant sections and writes an answer with citations to the source pages, grounded only in what your account can read. If your docs don’t cover it, it says so instead of inventing an answer. Agents ground their answers the same way through the connector.' },
  { q: 'Do I need to run anything extra for that?', a: 'Only if you self-host. Meaning-based search needs an embedding model, and ask-your-docs also needs an LLM — point tela at your own of each (the hosted instance has both set up). Keyword search always works on its own.' },
  { q: 'Is it really markdown, with all that block editing?', a: 'Yes. The editor is full block editing — drag, slash menu, turn-into, tables, diagrams — but pages.body is plain markdown. There is no block table; reordering a block reorders markdown lines. Import a directory, export anytime.' },
  { q: 'Can I edit in my own editor — Obsidian, VS Code?', a: 'Yes. Mount a space as a local folder over WebDAV and sync it with rclone, then edit the files in any editor you like. Pages round-trip as plain markdown and non-markdown files (images, PDFs, diagrams) sync too — so your local folder and tela stay in step both ways.' },
  { q: 'How do agents sign in?', a: 'Through the Claude and ChatGPT connectors they sign in once with OAuth — no token to handle. For code agents like Claude Code or Cursor, you create an access key that’s scoped to read or write, can expire, and can be limited to a single space.' },
  { q: 'Is my team’s data access-controlled?', a: 'Yes — SSO, organizations and groups, and per-space roles (owner / editor / viewer) with hard invariants. Keys are scoped and audited. The access model is documented and open.' },
  { q: 'What does it cost?', a: 'There’s a free tier for personal use and for small teams, paid Personal and Team tiers above them, and Enterprise for scale — or self-host it free. Tiers change your built-in AI limits (Atlas sources and monthly answers) and whether Atlas auto-refreshes on a schedule — never the product itself. Bring your own agent over MCP and it’s unlimited on any tier, including Free. Every new account starts on a 30-day Personal trial. Full breakdown on the pricing page.' },
  { q: 'Can I self-host it?', a: 'Yes. It’s open and self-hostable with Docker Compose (Postgres, plus an optional embedder for semantic search and an LLM for ask-your-docs). Your data on your disk, your markdown exportable. Self-host is the option, not the requirement — the hosted instance is ready to use now.' },
];
---
<section class="section section--tight">
  <div class="section-head reveal-up">
    <p class="kicker"><span class="kicker-dot"></span>Questions</p>
    <h2 class="h2">Straight answers.</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="faq reveal-up">
    {qs.map((item, i) => (
      <details class="qa" open={i === 0}>
        <summary class="q">
          <span>{item.q}</span>
          <svg class="chev" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"/></svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="a">{item.a}</p>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<script is:inline>
  (function () {
    document.querySelectorAll('.faq .qa').forEach(function (details) {
      details.addEventListener('toggle', function () {
        if (details.open && window.umami) {
          var q = details.querySelector('.q span');
          window.umami.track('faq-open', { question: q ? q.textContent.trim() : '' });
        }
      });
    });
  })();
</script>

<style>
  .faq { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); max-width: 52rem; }
  .qa { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .q {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 1rem;
    padding: 1.15rem 0.25rem;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--fg);
  }
  .q::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  .chev { color: var(--fg-faint); flex: none; transition: transform var(--dur) var(--ease-out); }
  .qa[open] .chev { transform: rotate(180deg); }
  .a {
    padding: 0 0.25rem 1.25rem;
    max-width: var(--measure);
    color: var(--fg-soft);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) { .chev { transition: none; } }
</style>
